cff-version: 1.2.0
message: "If you use this work, please cite it as below."
title: "Evaluating medical AI under missing information: same-provider judges and human raters change apparent safety"
authors:
  - family-names: Afrasyab
    given-names: Koyar
    affiliation: "Kinvectum AB"
type: article
year: 2026
license: CC-BY-4.0
abstract: >-
  An open-source study extending readiness stress-testing to open-ended medical
  conversation under missing information, across four frontier LLMs (Claude Opus 4.8,
  GPT-5.5, Grok 4.3, Gemini 3.5 Flash). It deletes clinical information from the final
  user turn and grades the response with a four-provider LLM-judge panel and a blinded
  clinician-anchored human reference. Two evaluator-facing findings: judge choice
  materially changes apparent safety (moderate inter-judge reliability; a same-provider
  preference that persists after adjusting for general judge severity), and LLM judges
  are systematically more permissive than clinicians. A closed-ended MedQA/MedMCQA
  anchor with paired statistics shows accuracy is high and option-order effects are
  within a five-point equivalence margin for three of four models.
references:
  - type: article
    title: "The Illusion of Readiness in Health AI"
    authors:
